dataIdInfo.idAbs: Annual five-year age group population estimates by sex for 2015 to 2030 for the national and first-order administrative division levels of Nepal were prepared by the U.S. Census Bureau for joining (linking) to shapefiles as attribute data. The estimates are consistent with the midyear national projections from the U.S. Census Bureau International Database (IDB).
dataIdInfo.idPurp: The U.S. Census Bureau is providing annual subnational five-year age group population estimates by sex for Nepal for 2015-2030 in a geographic information system (GIS) for users of the Spatial Data Repository, funded by the U.S. President’s Emergency Plan for AIDS Relief (PEPFAR).
dataIdInfo.idCredit:
CENSUS DATA 2021 Age-Sex Data: National Population and Housing Census 2021, Table 04: Population by Five Year Age Groups and Sex. Central Bureau of Statistics. Available online at http://censusnepal.cbs.gov.np/results/downloads/national (accessed April 04, 2023).
2011 Population Total Data: National Population and Housing Census 2011, Table 16: Population by 5 Years Age Group. Central Bureau of Statistics. Available online at http://unstats.un.org/unsd/demographic-social/census/documents/Nepal/Nepal-Census-2011-Vol1.pdf (accessed April 04, 2023).
The U.S. Census Bureau cannot guarantee the accuracy of non-U.S. census and survey data.
GEOSPATIAL BOUNDARIES International boundaries coincide with the Large Scale International Boundaries (LSIB) dataset from the U.S. Department of State, Office of the Geographer and Global Issues. Available online at http://geonode.state.gov (accessed April 04, 2023).
Geospatial data for the first-order administrative divisions of Nepal were downloaded from the United Nations Office for the Coordination of Humanitarian Affairs (OCHA), available online at http://data.humdata.org/dataset/administrative-bounadries-of-nepal, "Nepal - Subnational Administrative Boundaries" (accessed April 04, 2023).
The U.S. Census Bureau cannot guarantee the accuracy of boundary placements.
NATIONAL ESTIMATES AND PROJECTIONS U.S. Census Bureau, Population Division. International Database, December 2021 release, available online at http://www.census.gov/data-tools/demo/idb/ (accessed April 04, 2023).
NATIONAL AND SUBNATIONAL AREA NAMES AND CODES (1) U.S. National Geospatial-Intelligence Agency. NGA Geographic Names Server (GNS), available at http://geonames.nga.mil/geonames/GNSHome/welcome.html (accessed April 04, 2023). Contains geographic area names from the U.S. Board on Geographic Names and the U.S. Government Federal Information Processing System (FIPS) codes. (2) U.S. Government Geopolitical Entities, Names, and Codes (GENC) Standard. NSG Standards Registry, available at http://nsgreg.nga.mil/genc/discovery (accessed April 04, 2023).

dataIdInfo.suppInfo:
SUBNATIONAL DIVISIONS Nepal's first-order administrative divisions: 7 provinces as of the 2021 census.
SHAPEFILES The original shapefile downloaded from the United Nations Office for the Coordination of Humanitarian Affairs (OCHA) had 77 polygons and matched the 2021 census districts (second-order administrative divisions) with no changes to the subnational boundaries made by USCB staff. The U.S. Census Bureau aligned the shapefile's national boundary to the Large Scale International Boundary Line (LSIB) polygon file from the U.S. Department of State, Office of the Geographer and Global Issues. Finally, the LSIB-aligned shapefile was dissolved into 7 polygons, one for each of Nepal's first-order administrative divisions (provinces) as reported by the Central Bureau of Statistics in the 2021 census.
NOTES (1) Koshi province was previously named Province Number One. This name change has not yet been approved by the U.S. Board on Geographic Names Foreign Names Committee. (2) In 2015, Nawalparasi district split into Nawalparasi East and Nawalparasi West, and Rukum district split into Rukum East and Rukum West, as noted in the USCBCMNT field. Original 2011 population totals for these areas were split by USCB staff according to third-level administrative population totals within each of the new areas.
FEATURE AND ATTRIBUTE DETAILS The 2015-2030 population estimates for Nepal's administrative divisions are provided in the following two tables: (1) The Unicode tab-delimited text file (table) "Nepal_5yr_age_sex_2015-2030_uscb_jun2023.txt," which can be joined to the shapefile via the common field "GEO_MATCH." (2) The Excel table "Nepal_5yr_age_sex_2015-2030_508_uscb_jun2023.xlsx," formatted for accessibility in compliance with Section 508 of the U.S. Government's Federal Rehabilitation Act.
Details on processing of the census data and calculation of 2015-2030 estimates are provided in the "Census Metadata" tab of the Excel file and "Methods for Calculating 5-Year Age Group Population Estimates by Sex for Subnational Areas" document. For the subnational areas, the U.S. Board on Geographic Names (BGN) "approved" names from the NGA Geographic Names Server (cited in the "Credits") were used. For any area that a BGN name was not available, the name from the national census was used. Official codes for the subnational areas from the country's national statistical office, when available, are entered in the "NSO_CODE" field in both the text and Excel tables. Information on any alternative area names or recent name or boundary changes is entered in the "USCBCMNT" field. A partial list of the fields in the Excel and Unicode text files, including all fields identifying geographic names and codes, is provided in the Excel file's "Data Dictionary" tab. More detail on the U.S. Census Bureau subnational age and sex group estimates and maps for PEPFAR can be found in the document "Subnational Population Estimates Components for the Spatial Data Repository." It includes a data dictionary that is similar to that in the Excel table.
METHODOLOGY For more information, see the following methodology documents in the Spatial Data Repository: (1) "U.S. Census Bureau Methodology for SDR Subnational Population Estimates." (2) "U.S. Census Bureau Methods for Calculating 5-Year Age Group Population Estimates by Sex for Subnational Areas." (3) "Instructions for Joining Subnational Population Data to Shapefiles."
ACCESS The U.S. Census Bureau’s products for PEPFAR can be accessed from the Spatial Data Repository at http://spatialdata.dhsprogram.com/home/, which also provides access to data and maps from the DHS (Demographic and Health Surveys) Program. A zipped file containing shapefiles with metadata, an Excel workbook with subnational population estimates, and a Unicode tab-delimited text file is available for each country. PEPFAR products are also available on the Census Bureau website at http://www.census.gov/geographies/mapping-files/time-series/demo/international-programs/subnationalpopulation.html for download.
